# Spec 001 — Affordability + Commute Map (MVP)

Status: Draft
Owner: <you>
Related: none (first feature)

## Overview

Given a work location and a budget, show a Seattle-metro map that shades each
ZIP code by median home value and overlays a drive-time isochrone from the work
location, so a user can see at a glance which areas are both **affordable** and
**commutable**. The goal of this MVP is to prove the full pipeline end to end —
data in, two map layers out — not to be feature-complete.

## Context

- The app is market-level, not listing-level: it visualizes aggregate values by
  area, not individual properties.
- Two distinct contour fields are involved:
  - *Commute contours* (isochrones) come from the Mapbox Isochrone API.
  - The *cost surface* is derived by the app; for the MVP it is just the
    per-ZIP median value (a true blended surface is a later spec).
- Housing values come from a free aggregate dataset (Zillow ZHVI or Redfin
  Data Center), preprocessed to a small per-ZIP file.

## Requirements

- **R1 — Load housing data.** Load median home value by ZIP for the Seattle
  metro from a static, committed dataset.
  - Expected: backend exposes the per-ZIP values; missing/invalid ZIPs are
    skipped, not fatal.
- **R2 — Price choropleth.** Render a map where each ZIP's fill color encodes
  its median home value, with a legend.
- **R3 — Commute isochrone.** Given a hard-coded work lat/long, fetch a 30-min
  driving isochrone and overlay it as a contour on the map.
- **R4 — Budget filter.** Given a budget input, visually distinguish ZIPs at or
  under budget from those over budget.
- **R5 — Key safety.** The Mapbox token is used server-side only; it never
  appears in the frontend bundle or any client-side request.

## Non-functional / Constraints

- Use only free/aggregate housing data; no listing-level scraping.
- Initial map render < 2s on typical broadband.
- Scope is a single metro (Seattle) and a single hard-coded work location.

## Acceptance Criteria

- [ ] Loading the page shows the Seattle ZIP choropleth with a color legend.
- [ ] Entering a budget visibly greys out (or de-emphasizes) over-budget ZIPs.
- [ ] A 30-minute driving isochrone is visible and bounded by the road network
      (not a circle).
- [ ] The browser Network tab shows no Mapbox token in any client request.
- [ ] `pytest` passes for the backend; `npm run test` passes for the frontend.

## Out of Scope (explicit)

- Optimization and forecasting.
- A blended price+commute cost surface.
- Multiple metros; user-entered (dynamic) work location.
- Public-transit commute mode.
- User accounts or any persisted personal data.

## Verification notes

Each acceptance criterion traces to a requirement: choropleth → R1/R2, isochrone
→ R3, budget shading → R4, key absence → R5. Verify by walking this list
manually; the implementing agent does not self-certify done.